{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SVwQNUoEgWBNbtx1yHWYZw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The problem is very clear now: \n\n```\nfailed to start gossip client to ‹crdb-cluster-0.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local:26257›: initial connection heartbeat failed: grpc: ‹connection error: desc = \"transport: error while dialing: dial tcp: lookup crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local: no such host\"›\n```\n\nPod 1 (node 3) is trying to connect to pod 0, but when pod 0 responds, it's trying to connect BACK to `crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local` which is failing with \"no such host\".\nSo the root cause is DNS resolution: the cluster can't resolve the hostnames for pods 1 and 2 from within the pods themselves. This is odd because pod 1 should be able to resolve its own hostname, yet the gossip clients from pod 0 are failing to reach back to pods 1 and 2. So the gossip client on pod 1 connects to pod 0, but during the RPC handshake, pod 0 communicates information about pod 1's own address, and when pod 1 tries to resolve `crdb-cluster-1`, that lookup fails—which suggests the DNS isn't properly configured for the cluster members to discover each other. cluster-1 in the lookup error is puzzling since the connection target is pod 0. I'm wondering if CockroachDB's gossip protocol is involved here—maybe pod 0 is advertising its address back to pod 1, but something's getting mixed up with how the advertised address is being resolved or interpreted.\n\nActually, wait—the error is happening on pod 1 (n3), and it's trying to resolve `crdb-cluster-1`, which should be pod 1 itself. That's the real oddity here. This suggests there might be a DNS resolution issue with the headless service itself.\n\nI'm wondering if the problem is that the headless service only adds endpoints for Ready pods, and since pods 1 and 2 are failing their readiness probes, they're not getting DNS records. But StatefulSet pods should get DNS records based on their IP and hostname regardless of readiness status—let me verify that assumption against the Kubernetes documentation.\n\nActually, I need to test this directly. Since I can't use nslookup in the container, I'll try using the cockroach binary to check connectivity, or I could just look at the service endpoints to see what's actually registered.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3742,"cache_read_input_tokens":41646,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3742},"output_tokens":43,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57feb0c6-f11a-4e5d-a4d7-79f6638dafdd","uuid":"cb9df867-4608-4907-a56d-c11e0b267bd8","request_id":"req_011CccEEScb5KFa8tgda5gxp"}
