{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01J6qU89TJn1xrbzb9Dc2WZN","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"The 3-node CockroachDB cluster is fully deployed and healthy. Here's a summary of what was created and the one non-obvious fix required:\n\n**Resources deployed:**\n- `Service/crdb-cluster` — headless service (grpc 26257, http 8080), selector on both required labels\n- `Service/crdb-cluster-public` — ClusterIP service for external SQL/HTTP access\n- `StatefulSet/crdb-cluster` — 3 replicas, `podManagementPolicy: Parallel`, image `v24.1.0`, 10Gi PVC per pod, insecure mode with full `--join` list\n- `PodDisruptionBudget/crdb-cluster-pdb` — `minAvailable: 2` enforces quorum preservation\n\n**Two fixes needed during bring-up:**\n\n1. **`podManagementPolicy: Parallel`** — without it, the StatefulSet waits for pod 0 to be Ready before creating pods 1 and 2, but pod 0 can't become Ready until `cockroach init` is run (which needs all nodes up). Parallel starts all 3 pods at once.\n\n2. **`publishNotReadyAddresses: true` on the headless service** — CockroachDB nodes gossip using their per-pod DNS names. With the default behavior, Kubernetes only creates DNS A records for Ready pods, so pods 1 and 2 couldn't resolve each other's names (`crdb-cluster-1.crdb-cluster.cockroachdb.svc.cluster.local: no such host`). Setting this flag publishes DNS for all pods regardless of readiness, allowing the cluster to bootstrap.\n\nAfter patching the headless service, all 3 nodes joined and became `is_available: true, is_live: true`. The PDB allows at most 1 voluntary disruption, preserving quorum."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":660,"cache_read_input_tokens":51374,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":660},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"conte